    "summary": "The Decembrist Revolt of 14 December 1825 was an uprising by a group of reform-minded Russian army officers in St. Petersburg, timed to coincide with the interregnum following Tsar Alexander I's death. The revolt was quickly suppressed, but the Decembrists — as they came to be known — became martyrs and founding figures of the Russian revolutionary tradition, immortalized in literature and revered by subsequent generations of reformers and revolutionaries.\n\nThe conspirators were mostly young officers of the imperial guard who had been exposed to liberal and constitutional ideas during the campaigns of the [[event:109|Napoleonic Wars]] and had encountered Western European societies firsthand. They were appalled at the contrast between the constitutional governments they had observed in France and the continuing autocracy and serfdom of Russia. Divided between a moderate 'Northern Society' that sought a constitutional monarchy and a more radical 'Southern Society' that envisioned a republic, they took advantage of the confusion over the succession between Grand Duke Constantine and Nicholas I to stage their revolt.\n\nAbout 3,000 soldiers assembled in Senate Square in St. Petersburg, refusing to swear the oath to Nicholas. Their hopes of triggering a broader popular uprising were not realized; the rebel force stood in the square for hours without a clear plan. By evening Nicholas had gathered loyal troops and artillery sufficient to disperse the revolt with cannon fire. Five ringleaders were subsequently hanged; over a hundred others were imprisoned or exiled to Siberia. Nicholas I drew the lesson that Russia needed tighter autocratic control and more vigorous suppression of liberal ideas — inaugurating a repressive reign that lasted until his death in 1855.",
    "wikipedia_url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Decembrist_revolt",
